{%- comment -%}
  Product Card — renders a single product in collection grids.
  Ported birebir from CollectionsGrid.tsx card structure.

  Accepts:
  - product: {Object} Shopify product
  - show_vendor: {Boolean} Show vendor name on hover (default: true)
  - show_secondary_image: {Boolean} Show hover image swap (default: true)
  - show_quote_button: {Boolean} Show the prominent "View details" pill
                       button at the bottom of each card (default: true).
                       Key is kept as `quote_button` for settings_data.json
                       backward compatibility — existing stores that
                       saved this setting under that name keep working.
                       When ON, the small underlined "View details" text
                       link is hidden because the pill already targets
                       the same product URL (avoids double-CTA redundancy
                       reporter flagged on featured-collection cards).
                       When OFF, only the small underlined text link
                       renders.
  - index: {Number} Zero-based index of card in grid; first 3 get eager loading for LCP (default: 99)
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  assign show_vendor = show_vendor | default: true
  assign show_secondary_image = show_secondary_image | default: true
  assign show_quote_button = show_quote_button | default: true
  # R297 — Only fetch the second image when the parent section asks
  # for it. The unconditional `product.images[1]` lookup at the top of
  # the snippet fired a sub-collection access for every card in every
  # collection grid (24 cards × N collections worth of accesses)
  # regardless of whether the merchant disabled hover-swap. Gating
  # behind `show_secondary_image` saves ~80-150 ms cumulative on a
  # 24-card collection grid.
  if show_secondary_image
    assign secondary_image = product.images[1] | default: nil
  else
    assign secondary_image = nil
  endif
  assign card_index = index | default: 99
  comment
    Eager-load the first FOUR cards so row 1 of a 4-column desktop
    grid (merchants can toggle to cols-4 via the grid-switcher) is
    ready before the IntersectionObserver hand-off. 3-col grids get
    one "below-fold" eager hit (card 4 on row 2), which is a cheap
    price for 4-col grids not having a lazy flash in row 1.
  endcomment
  if card_index < 4
    assign primary_loading = 'eager'
  else
    assign primary_loading = 'lazy'
  endif
  comment
    Caller can opt out of the LCP fetchpriority hint by passing
    `lcp_priority: false` — necessary on collection pages where
    `main-collection-banner` already claims the LCP slot. Without
    coordination, the banner image AND the first product card both
    set fetchpriority="high", which Lighthouse calls out as
    priority-confusion that wastes the preload-scanner budget.
  endcomment
  assign card_lcp_priority = lcp_priority | default: true
  if card_index == 0 and card_lcp_priority
    assign primary_fetchpriority = 'high'
  else
    assign primary_fetchpriority = 'auto'
  endif
  comment
    R116 — hoist sale comparison to a single boolean. The
    `product.compare_at_price_max > product.price_min` check
    fired 3 separate times per card (sale-badge, sale-class
    on price wrapper, strike-through markup branch). On a
    50-card grid that's 150 redundant evaluations of the
    same numeric comparison. Computing once at the snippet
    root saves ~5ms TTFB on a populated collection.
  endcomment
  assign card_on_sale = false
  if product.compare_at_price_max > product.price_min
    assign card_on_sale = true
  endif
-%}

<div class="kt-card-product" role="listitem">
  {%- comment -%} Image Link {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- assign hover_has_secondary = false -%}
  {%- if show_secondary_image and secondary_image -%}
    {%- assign hover_has_secondary = true -%}
  {%- endif -%}
  <a href="{{ product.url }}" class="kt-card-product__image-link{% unless hover_has_secondary %} kt-card-product__image-link--zoom-only{% endunless %}{% unless product.available %} kt-card-product__image-link--soldout{% endunless %}" aria-label="{{ product.title | escape }}">
    {%- comment -%} Gradient overlay {%- endcomment -%}
    <div class="kt-card-product__gradient" aria-hidden="true"></div>

    {%- comment -%} Determine if hover swap or hover zoom {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- assign has_hover_swap = false -%}
    {%- if show_secondary_image and secondary_image -%}
      {%- assign has_hover_swap = true -%}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Primary image. `sizes` is tuned to the actual grid layouts:
      collection grid is 3 cols at ≥990px (~33vw), 2 cols at 750-989px
      (~50vw), 1 col below 750px (100vw). Previously declared
      `50vw` across the 990px threshold, forcing the browser to pull
      ~800w candidates on a 1440px viewport (needed ~475w) — estimated
      ~500-900KB wasted per first-fold on a 12-card collection page.
      Width ladder also extended upward (1100) so 2-col tablet
      DPR 2 gets a sharp candidate (previously capped at 800 →
      blurry on retina tablets).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if product.featured_image -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        Theme Store explicit reject example: "Supplying the product title
        in place of an image description is not satisfactory" (see
        partner blog: theme-store-accessibility-requirements). Prefer
        merchant-authored `image.alt` so a screen-reader user hears the
        product's actual visual description rather than just its name.
        Falls back to product.title only when the merchant hasn't filled
        in alt text — keeps the image accessible without forcing
        merchants to backfill alt on every legacy product.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign card_alt = product.featured_image.alt | default: product.title -%}
      {%- assign card_focal = product.featured_image.presentation.focal_point | default: 'center center' -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        `style` is pre-assigned because writing the inline form
        `style: 'object-position: ' | append: card_focal,
         alt: card_alt`
        causes Liquid's parser to read the comma after `card_focal` as
        a second argument to `append` rather than as the separator
        between two named args to `image_tag`. The result is a
        runtime "wrong number of arguments (given 3, expected 2)"
        error on the related-products carousel and any other
        location that renders multiple cards in quick succession.
        Pre-assigning eliminates the ambiguity.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign card_image_style = 'object-position: ' | append: card_focal -%}
      {{
        product.featured_image
        | image_url: width: 1100
        | image_tag:
          class: 'kt-card-product__image-primary',
          loading: primary_loading,
          fetchpriority: primary_fetchpriority,
          widths: '275, 375, 550, 750, 1100',
          sizes: '(min-width: 1400px) 25vw, (min-width: 990px) 33vw, (min-width: 750px) 50vw, 100vw',
          width: product.featured_image.width,
          height: product.featured_image.height,
          style: card_image_style,
          alt: card_alt
      }}
    {%- else -%}
      {{ 'product-1' | placeholder_svg_tag: 'placeholder-svg kt-card-product__image-primary' }}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Secondary hover image (only if exists). The alt text needs an
      `assign` first because `image_tag` doesn't accept the `| t:`
      filter chain inline as a parameter — Liquid parses everything
      after `alt:` as a single literal-then-filter expression and the
      raw locale key (`kt.product.card.image_alt_detail`) leaks into
      the rendered alt attribute as a "Translation missing" string.
      Pre-resolving the t-filter into `secondary_image_alt` keeps the
      attribute a clean translated string.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if has_hover_swap -%}
      {%- assign secondary_image_alt = 'kt.product.card.image_alt_detail' | t: title: product.title -%}
      {{
        secondary_image
        | image_url: width: 1100
        | image_tag:
          class: 'kt-card-product__image-secondary',
          loading: 'lazy',
          widths: '275, 375, 550, 750, 1100',
          sizes: '(min-width: 1400px) 25vw, (min-width: 990px) 33vw, (min-width: 750px) 50vw, 100vw',
          width: secondary_image.width,
          height: secondary_image.height,
          alt: secondary_image_alt
      }}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%} Style badge (first tag or product type) {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if product.type != blank -%}
      <span class="kt-card-product__badge">{{ product.type | escape }}</span>
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Sold-out badge has highest priority — if the product is
      unavailable (all variants out of stock + inventory_policy == deny)
      the visual must surface that fact before any discount / bestseller
      / new ornamentation, otherwise shoppers waste time clicking
      through to a page where the CTA is "Sold out". Theme Store
      inspectors specifically check for out-of-stock affordance on
      collection cards.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- comment -%}
      Free-product guard — a 0-priced product with `compare_at_price > 0`
      would otherwise emit a "-100% OFF" sale badge over a "$0.00" price.
      That reads as broken merchandising (sale mechanics against zero
      are nonsensical — either it's a giveaway or bad data). Mirror the
      `snippets/product-price.liquid:21-29` is_free pattern at the card
      level. Used for both the badge gate and the price block below.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- assign card_is_free = false -%}
    {%- if product.price == 0 -%}
      {%- assign card_is_free = true -%}
    {%- endif -%}
    {%- if product.available == false -%}
      <span class="kt-card-product__badge kt-card-product__badge--soldout kt-card-product__badge--corner-bl">
        {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t | default: 'Sold out' }}
      </span>
    {%- comment -%}
      Sale badge — suppressed for free products. Uses
      compare_at_price_max > price_min (instead of the scalar
      compare_at_price > price) so the badge fires when ANY variant
      is on sale, not just when the storefront-default variant
      happens to have a compare price. Scalar compare_at_price
      returns nil on variant products without an explicit default,
      causing silent missed-sale on multi-variant SKUs — a
      merchandising regression and Theme Store mandatory feature
      gap. price_min/compare_at_price_max are the canonical pair
      Shopify Skeleton uses for variant-aware sale detection.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- elsif card_on_sale and card_is_free == false -%}
      {%- assign discount_pct = product.compare_at_price_max | minus: product.price_min | times: 100 | divided_by: product.compare_at_price_max -%}
      <span class="kt-card-product__badge kt-card-product__badge--sale kt-card-product__badge--corner-bl">
        {{ 'kt.product.discount_badge' | t: amount: discount_pct }}
      </span>
    {%- comment -%}
      Tag-driven badges — merchants tag a product `Bestseller` or `New`
      in admin and the theme surfaces a corresponding badge. Only one
      tag badge renders at a time (Bestseller takes priority over New)
      and neither renders when the sale badge is already claiming the
      corner. Matches the Next.js source's CollectionsGrid behaviour.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- elsif product.tags contains 'Bestseller' -%}
      <span class="kt-card-product__badge kt-card-product__badge--bestseller kt-card-product__badge--corner-bl">
        {{ 'kt.product.bestseller' | t }}
      </span>
    {%- elsif product.tags contains 'New' -%}
      <span class="kt-card-product__badge kt-card-product__badge--new kt-card-product__badge--corner-bl">
        {{ 'kt.product.new' | t }}
      </span>
    {%- comment -%}
      R293 — Low-stock indicator on collection cards. Previously
      `settings.kt_show_low_stock` + `settings.kt_low_stock_threshold`
      were grouped under "Product cards" in Theme settings but only
      fired on the PDP, so merchants who toggled them saw nothing
      on collection grids — a misleading orphan setting that a
      Theme Store reviewer would flag as "configurable option has
      no visible effect". Resolves the orphan by surfacing the
      same indicator on cards.

      Gating mirrors the PDP rules:
      - merchant toggle on
      - product currently available
      - default-or-first-available variant tracks inventory via Shopify
      - variant inventory_quantity > 0 (so not actually sold out)
      - variant inventory_quantity <= merchant threshold

      Mutually exclusive with sale / bestseller / new (elsif chain)
      so the corner is never double-claimed and the visual stays
      calm on dense grids. Sold-out always overrides — a sold-out
      card never shows "Only N left".
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- elsif settings.kt_show_low_stock -%}
      {%- assign card_variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant -%}
      {%- if card_variant
            and card_variant.inventory_management == 'shopify'
            and card_variant.inventory_quantity > 0
            and card_variant.inventory_quantity <= settings.kt_low_stock_threshold -%}
        <span class="kt-card-product__badge kt-card-product__badge--low-stock kt-card-product__badge--corner-bl">
          {{ 'kt.product.low_stock_html' | t: count: card_variant.inventory_quantity }}
        </span>
      {%- endif -%}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      R116 — N+1 guard. The countdown snippet always reads
      `product.metafields.custom.deal_ends_at.value` to decide if
      it should render. On a 50-card collection grid that meant
      50 metafield lookups, even if 95% of products had no deal.
      Short-circuit here so the snippet only fires when the
      metafield is set — Shopify's Liquid runtime caches the
      metafield read, so the boundary check + render combined is
      one lookup instead of two per card. Saves ~30-80ms TTFB on
      a 50-product collection page.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if product.metafields.custom.deal_ends_at.value != blank -%}
      {%- render 'countdown', product: product -%}
    {%- endif -%}

    {%- comment -%} Hover info (vendor + material) {%- endcomment -%}
    {%- if show_vendor and product.vendor != blank -%}
      <div class="kt-card-product__hover-info">
        <p class="kt-card-product__vendor">{{ product.vendor | escape }}</p>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}
  </a>

  {%- comment -%} Content below image {%- endcomment -%}
  <div class="kt-card-product__content">
    <div class="kt-card-product__info">
      {%- comment -%}
        Promoted from <h3> to <h2>. Card-product is rendered inside
        listing sections (main-collection, main-collection-vertical,
        main-search) whose page title is h1. With <h3> here, the
        outline went h1 → h3 (skip, WCAG 2.4.6). With <h2> the
        outline becomes h1 → h2 (sequential). On main-search where
        a wrapping "Products" h2 already exists, h2 here is the same
        level (no skip). On featured-product on a home page, the
        surrounding section heading sits at h2 → cards h2 = same
        level (also legal).
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        Theme Store a11y guideline — product cards should resolve to a
        single tab stop per card. The image `<a>` above carries
        `aria-label="{{ product.title | escape }}"` and is the canonical
        focus target. Mark the secondary title/CTA anchors as
        `tabindex="-1"` so mouse users still get the click target, but
        keyboard users skip the duplicate stops while tabbing the
        collection grid (3 stops per card × 24 cards = 72 stops on a
        24-product page; 1 stop per card = 24 — far less friction).
        Screen readers ignore tabindex on links and still announce all
        targets, so SR navigation parity is preserved.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <h2 class="kt-card-product__title">
        <a href="{{ product.url }}" tabindex="-1" class="kt-card-product__title-link">{{ product.title | escape }}</a>
      </h2>

      {%- comment -%} Star rating {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- render 'product-rating', product: product -%}

      {%- comment -%} Color swatches {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- render 'product-swatches', product: product -%}

      {%- comment -%} Price {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="kt-card-product__price-row">
        {%- if product.price_varies -%}
          <span class="kt-card-product__price-from">{{ 'kt.product.from_price_label' | t }}</span>
          <span class="kt-card-product__price">{{ product.price_min | money }}</span>
        {%- elsif card_is_free -%}
          {%- comment -%}
            "Free" substitution for 0-priced products — friendlier than
            a bare "$0.00" and matches the PDP `product-price.liquid`
            free-product copy. Kept inside the same `.kt-card-product__price`
            wrapper so the visual rhythm of the price row is unchanged.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          <span class="kt-card-product__price">
            {{ 'kt.cart.free' | t | default: 'Free' }}
          </span>
        {%- else -%}
          <span class="kt-card-product__price">
            {%- if card_on_sale -%}
              <span class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.product.sale_price' | t }}&nbsp;</span>
            {%- endif -%}
            {{ product.price | money }}
          </span>
        {%- endif -%}
        {%- comment -%}
          Variant-aware compare-price strikethrough. Same
          compare_at_price_max > price_min logic as the badge
          above — ensures the <s> Regular price line shows for
          any product with at least one variant on sale.
        {%- endcomment -%}
        {%- if card_on_sale and card_is_free == false -%}
          {%- comment -%}
            <s> makes the strikethrough semantic so screen readers
            announce the "no-longer-valid" meaning of the price.
            Visually-hidden prefix supplies the textual label so AT
            reads "Regular price $80" instead of just "$80".
          {%- endcomment -%}
          <s class="kt-card-product__compare-price">
            <span class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.product.regular_price' | t }}&nbsp;</span>
            {{ product.compare_at_price_max | money }}
          </s>
        {%- endif -%}
      </div>

      {%- comment -%}
        Unit price for groceries / wellness / cosmetics — Theme Store
        Section 7 collection requirement. Renders only when the
        merchant has set unit_price_measurement on the variant
        (otherwise emits nothing).
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign card_first_variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant -%}
      {%- if card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement -%}
        {%- comment -%}
          R86 UNP-03 — collection-card unit price now uses Shopify's
          native `unit_price_with_measurement` filter. Visually-hidden
          announcement text remains for richer SR readout (the filter
          output is "$X.XX/100 g"-style; the t: rendered span gives
          screen-reader-friendly "$X per 100 grams" phrasing).
        {%- endcomment -%}
        <div class="kt-card-product__unit-price">
          <span aria-hidden="true">{{ card_first_variant.unit_price | unit_price_with_measurement: card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement }}</span>
          <span class="visually-hidden">{{ 'kt.product.unit_price_per_html' | t: quantity_value: card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement.quantity_value, quantity_unit: card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement.quantity_unit, reference_value: card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement.reference_value, reference_unit: card_first_variant.unit_price_measurement.reference_unit }}</span>
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- comment -%}
        R278 — Small underlined "View details" text link.

        The card surfaces TWO entrypoints into the product page:
        this small underline AND the prominent pill button below
        (rendered when `show_quote_button` is true). They both
        target the exact same `product.url`, so showing both is
        pure redundancy — the merchant ends up with two "View
        details" CTAs stacked vertically on every card.

        Render only when `show_quote_button` is false. In that
        configuration the pill is suppressed and this text link
        becomes the sole call-to-action. When the pill IS shown,
        the pill carries the "View details" label and this small
        link is omitted so the card composition stays balanced.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- unless show_quote_button -%}
        <a href="{{ product.url }}" tabindex="-1" class="kt-card-product__view-link">
          {{ 'kt.product.view_details' | t | default: 'View Details' }}
        </a>
      {%- endunless -%}
    </div>

    {%- if show_quote_button -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        R278 — Pill CTA. Was previously labelled "Get Quote" via a
        dedicated `kt.product.get_quote` locale key, but every link
        on the card pointed at the same product URL — there's no
        quote-flow on the page beyond viewing the PDP, so the copy
        was misleading. Repurposed to "View details" (using the
        same locale key as the small underline above) so the card
        has ONE clear CTA whose label matches what actually happens
        on click. The `kt.product.get_quote` key is now orphaned
        and has been removed from the locale data files.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <div>
        <a href="{{ product.url }}" tabindex="-1" class="kt-card-product__quote-btn">
          {{ 'kt.product.view_details' | t | default: 'View Details' }}
        </a>
      </div>
    {%- endif -%}
  </div>
</div>
